'''Guayaquil Sport Club''' was an [[Ecuador]]ian football club based in [[Guayaquil]]. It was the first football club in the country, has founded on April 23, 1899<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/ecuafound.html |title=Ecuador – Foundation Dates of Clubs |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |first=Esteban |last=Ávila Villagómez |date=October 8, 2010 |accessdate=October 16, 2010 }}</ref> by Juan Wright and Roberto Wright, the two brothers who brought the sport to the country.
The club's only title came in the amateur era of Guayaquil football, when it won the regional league in 1943. It also played one season the top-flight [[Ecuadorian Serie A|Serie A]] in [[1973 Campeonato Ecuatoriano de Fútbol Serie A|1973]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/ecua73.html |title=Ecuador 1973 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |first=Fernando |last=Espinoza Añazco |date=February 23, 2003 |accessdate=October 16, 2010 }}</ref> where it finished 12th. The club ceased operation in 1990 after 91 years of existence and has refounded on February 5, 2014.
==Achievements== '''Campeonato Amateur del Guayas''' *'''Champion (1):''' 1943<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/ecua-amachamp.html |title=Ecuador – List of Amateur Champions Guayas and Pichincha |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |first=Fernando |last=Espinoza Añazco |date=March 25, 2010 |accessdate=October 16, 2010}}</ref>
